<span id="freeTextContainer17087455217646736496">I honestly couldn&apos;t stomach this book. I was invested in the others and so the twist in this one had me cringing all the way through. I know people were ecstatic and loving this book but really the way ruin is being forced into these feelings doesn&apos;t sit well with me. Atleast with what happens at the end of book 3 I believed in the love he had for Is. And was hoping that there was going to be some positive outcome for them, some sort of loophole because this fourth book was just cruel and soo un</span>
  <span id="freeText17087455217646736496" style="display:none">I honestly couldn't stomach this book. I was invested in the others and so the twist in this one had me cringing all the way through. I know people were ecstatic and loving this book but really the way ruin is being forced into these feelings doesn't sit well with me. Atleast with what happens at the end of book 3 I believed in the love he had for Is. And was hoping that there was going to be some positive outcome for them, some sort of loophole because this fourth book was just cruel and soo unforgiving to their 'sacred joining'. I didn't even see the point in emphasising how beautiful their link was and how everyone on the side of 'good' was so happy about it, just to have it twist the way it did. I won't be picking up the next book, won't be able to stomach reading how someone who classified themselves as a man is being forced to 'be a woman' just for a prophecy when Isabel could've easily been brought back (reincarnation happens or a spell sheesh angels from the 'good' side, even God could duh!) for the prophecy since it is paranormal. And has to do with God and a biblical prophecy, miracles should've been happening regarding their happily ever after, preserving their 'sacred joining'. Like why did I waste my time, that I could've used on another story, with ruin and Is, it's like a slap in the face. Well that's the end of my mini rant</span>
